<fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Longleftarrow )]]></fr:tex> Suppose <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[[\mathbb {F}(\alpha ) : \mathbb {F}]]]></fr:tex> is finite. Define
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {split}T\colon &\mathbb {F}(\alpha )\to \mathbb {F}(\alpha )\\ &x\mapsto \alpha  x\end {split}]]></fr:tex>
Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex> is a linear operator on a finite-diumensional vector space. So it has a <fr:link
type="local"
href="iaa-0009.xml"
addr="iaa-0009"
title="Traditional Introduction to Modules">minimal polynomial as a linear operator</fr:link>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m(x)]]></fr:tex> be this minimal polynomial for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex>. We find <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m(T)]]></fr:tex> sends <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\mapsto  m(\alpha )x]]></fr:tex>, but we also know <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m(\alpha )=0]]></fr:tex> by the <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-0052.xml"
addr="ra-0052"
title="Cayley-Hamilton theorem">Cayley-Hamilton theorem</fr:link>.</fr:p><html:span
